    {
      "turn_number": 9,
      "role": "interviewer",
      "type": "question",
      "text": "During pregnancy, what did you expect in terms of how your changing body would be discussed and examined by healthcare providers? And how did those interactions actually feel?",
      "question_id": "V4_PREG_Q04",
      "probe_id": null,
      "target_dimensions": [
        "latent_needs",
        "motivations"
      ],
      "target_latent": [
        "body_image_autonomy",
        "dignity_respect"
      ],
      "input_tokens": 0,
      "output_tokens": 0
    },
    {
      "turn_number": 10,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I thought people would actually talk to me — like, sit down and explain why my belly is doing what it’s doing, what’s normal, what to watch for. I wanted gentle exams, someone who’d say, “It’s okay to worry,” and not act like I was being dramatic for asking about every ache and stretch mark. I expected a midwife who knew my name, my job schedule, and that I stay up reading about SIDS at night.\n\nIn reality it’s been mixed. The first few visits felt clinical and fast — checklists, measurements, “low-risk” said almost like a mic drop. I found myself nodding so hard just to keep things moving. Some providers were kind and explained kicks or Braxton Hicks; others did quick belly checks without much context, leaving me Googling things afterward. Pelvic exams felt awkward and rushed sometimes; I left feeling a little embarrassed instead of reassured. When I asked about body changes — the weight, the swelling, the insomnia — I often had to push for detail. It made me more determined to learn everything myself, which is exhausting.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "V4_PREG_Q04",
      "input_tokens": 883,
      "output_tokens": 490
    },
    {
      "turn_number": 11,
      "role": "interviewer",
      "type": "probe",
      "text": "Were there any examinations or conversations about your body that left you feeling uncomfortable or unprepared? What happened?",
